  "text": "By Assumptions 1(d) and 1(e), when d < q we allow the dynamics of the factors to be driven by (q − d) < q unit roots implying the presence of (q − d) common trends [CITATION_1] . Clearly, in this setting, the factors are cointegrated with cointegration rank d, thus representing the permanent and transitory aspects of macroeconomic dynamics. When d = 0-i.e., the dynamics of the factors are driven by q unit roots-the VAR for the common factors in levels in (2) does not exist; instead, it exists a VAR for ∆f t , or the factors can be modeled as q independent random walks as in [CITATION_2] . That said, the case d > 0 is the relevant one, as there is full agreement in the economic profession that while some fluctuations in the economy are permanent (common trends), some others are only temporary.",
